You have this line:

```tsx
const [items, setItems] = useState(getSavedData() || initialData || []);
```
JavaScript works with Applicative Order, so `getSavedData()` is called.

Internally that functions does this check:

```tsx
	const getSavedData = () => {
		var savedData = null;
		if (typeof window != undefined) {
			savedData = localStorage.getItem(STORE_SELECTION)
				? JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(STORE_SELECTION))
				: null;
			return savedData;
		}
		return savedData;
	};
```

Never mind the usage of `var`, let's look at this `if` branch:

```js
		if (typeof window != undefined) {
```

That's not the check you want!

```console
Welcome to Node.js v18.18.0.
Type ".help" for more information.
> typeof window != undefined
true
```

As you can see, in Node, this if branch does run. You want something like `if (typeof window !== 'undefined')`, because the `typeof` operator returns a string.

- https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/typeof

The error message you're encountering,
```
Refused to frame 'https://www.bseindia.com/' because an ancestor violates the following Content Security Policy directive: 'frame-ancestors 'self'.
```
indicates that the target website https://www.bseindia.com/ has a Content Security Policy (CSP) in place, restricting the framing of its content in iframes.

Specifically, the CSP directive frame-ancestors 'self' in the error message means that only the same origin (same domain, protocol, and port) is allowed to frame the content of the target website.

Since your webpage is attempting to embed content from https://www.bseindia.com/ within an iframe, and this action violates the CSP directive of the target website, the browser refuses to load the iframe and reports the mentioned error.

Solutions:
1. Coordinate with the target website: If you have the appropriate permissions and are legitimately embedding content from the target website, you can contact the administrators of the target website and request to add your webpage to the whitelist in their CSP.
2. Use a backend proxy: Proxy the requests for the target PDF file through your own server and pass the proxy's result to your frontend. This way, the target website won't be directly loaded in the iframe, and the request will be made from your domain, bypassing the CSP restrictions of the target website.
Keep in mind that the second solution requires server-side configuration and handling.

In Next.js, you can resolve the issue by configuring `rewrites` in `next.config.js.`
```ts
// next.config.js
module.exports = {
  async rewrites() {
    return [
      {
        source: '/bseindia/:path*',
        destination: 'https://www.bseindia.com/:path*',
      },
    ]
  },
}
```
