This is working as expected, but heard we can make this behavior more clear. I [just made a video](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VBlSe8tvg4U) walking through caching that hopefully will help explain a little bit more. In the instance of the example you provided, a couple things I wanted to mention.

First, rather than using the route segment config options, prefer to use functions like `noStore()` or `cookies()` / `headers()` etc for opt-ing the page into dynamic rendering. This is more commonly how your application will be structured – e.g. this can be a nested component, not necessarily at the top level of the page or layout.

```js
import React from 'react';
import Link from 'next/link';
import { unstable_noStore as noStore } from 'next/cache';

export default function Page() {
  noStore();
  return (
    <main>
      <h1>A: {Date.now()}</h1>
      <Link href="/">Back</Link>
    </main>
  );
}
```

Second, if you want to see a new date value on transition here, you can use `<a>` instead:

```js
export default function Home() {
  return (
    <main>
      <section>
        <a href="/test">Test</a>
      </section>
    </main>
  );
}
```

I understand the date example is commonly used to try and reason about how the system works (that's what I used in my video, too!) but more commonly, there will be some change to your underlying data (whether that's a `fetch` or some database call that you wrap with `unstable_cache`) and you'd use the Next.js APIs to invalidate the cache (`revalidateTag` and `revalidatePath`) which would ensure that new data is fresh on the page transition. Hope this helps! And as mentioned above, there's a [bunch more detail here](https://github.com/vercel/next.js/discussions/54075), as well as the docs, and we're exploring some further options to customize caching.

